			<div class="post-6617 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-germany-2 category-italy">

				<div class="entry">

					<h2><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/09/05/merkel-asks-italy-to-delay-bailout-request-report-marketwatch/">Merkel asks Italy to delay bailout request: report&nbsp;[Marketwatch]</a></h2>

					<div class="post-info">
						<p>
							<span class="time">September 5, 2012</span>
															<span class="author">by <a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/author/mktgeistmike/" title="Posts by mktgeistmike" rel="author">mktgeistmike</a></span>
																						<span class="post-comments"><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/09/05/merkel-asks-italy-to-delay-bailout-request-report-marketwatch/#respond" title="Comment on Merkel asks Italy to delay bailout request: report&nbsp;[Marketwatch]">Leave a comment</a></span>
																				</p>
					</div>

					<p>By Barbara Kollmeyer</p>
<div>
<article>
<p id="">MADRID (MarketWatch) &#8212; German Chancellor Angela Merkel has asked Italian Prime Minister Mario Monti to hold off on a request for a bailout, according to a report in Spanish daily El Mundo on Friday. Merkel reportedly made the request to Monti at their meeting in Berlin on Wednesday, and the newspaper said she would make the same request of Spanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy when they meet next Thursday. The efforts by Merkel are reportedly aimed at calming an internal crisis at the Bundesbank, whose central bank chief, Jens Weidmann, is strongly opposed to any action by the European Central Bank to buy Spanish or Italian government bonds. German newspaper Bild reported in its online edition on Friday that Weidmann has been considering his resignation in recent weeks.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="http://www.marketwatch.com/story/merkel-asks-italy-to-delay-bailout-request-report-2012-08-31">Read more</a></p>
</article>
</div>
<div class="clear"></div>

				</div>

